07929nam a2200937Ia 9781501731686DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182002nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017316867 a10.7591/97815017316862doi  a(DE-B1597)515428  a(OCoLC)1076751987  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD58.6.N468 2003 7aBUS0470002bisacsh04a658.4/04200aNegotiations and Change :bFrom the Workplace to Society /ced. by David B. Lipsky, Thomas A. Kochan. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b13 charts, 20 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The Behavioral Theory of Negotiations -- t1. Conceptual Foundations: Walton and McKersie's Subprocesses of Negotiations -- t2. New Directions in Teaching Negotiations: From Walton and McKersie to the New Millennium -- tPART II: WORKPLACE CHANGE AND TACIT NEGOTIATIONS -- t3. Changing Psychological Contracts: Implications for Human Resource Management and Industrial Relations -- t4. Changing Relations between Supervisors and Employees: From Deal Making to Strategic Negotiations -- t5. New Forms of Work Groups: Exocentric Teams Paul S. Goodman -- t6. Leaning toward Teams: Divergent and Convergent Trends in Diffusion of Lean Production Work Practices -- t7. Workplace Justice, Zero Tolerance, and Zero Barriers Mary Rowe -- tPART III: TRANSFORMATIONS IN LABOR-MANAGEMENT RELATIONS -- t8. How Process Matters: A Five-Phase Model for Examining Interest-Based Bargaining -- t9. Collective Bargaining and Human Resource Management in Britain: Can Partnership Square the Circle? -- t10. Partnerships and Flexible Networks: Alternatives or Complementary Models of Labor-Management Relations? -- t11. The Truth about Corporate Governance -- t12. Union-Nominated Directors: A New Voice in Corporate Governance -- t13. Negotiating Equality? Women, Work, and Organized Labor in the European Union -- tPART IV: NEGOTIATIONS IN OTHER ARENAS -- t14. Applying the Insights of Walton and McKersie to the Environmental Context -- t15. Collective Bargaining and Public Policy Dispute Resolution: Similarities and Differences -- t16. Negotiating Identity: First-Person Plural Subjective Lavinia Hall -- tPART V: THE FUTURE OF NEGOTIATIONS -- t17. From the Behavioral Theory to the Future of Negotiations -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMajor changes within and between organizations are now generally negotiated by the parties that have a stake in the consequences of the changes. This was not always so. In 1965, with A Behavioral Theory of Labor Negotiations, Richard Walton and Robert McKersie laid the analytical foundation for much of the innovation in the practice of negotiation that has occurred over the last thirty-nine years. Since that time, however, the field has undergone significant changes, and Walton and McKersie's ideas have been applied to a wide variety of situations beyond labor negotiations.Negotiations and Change represents the next generation of thinking. Experts on negotiations, management, and organizational behavior take stock of what has been learned since 1965. They extend and apply the concepts of Walton and McKersie and of other leaders in the study of negotiations to a broad range of business, professional, and personal concerns: workplace teams, conflict management systems, corporate governance, and environmental disputes. While building on those foundations, the essays demonstrate the continued robustness and relevance of Walton and McKersie's behavioral theory by suggesting ways it could be used to improve the management of change. Returning to its roots, the volume concludes with a retrospective by Richard Walton and Robert McKersie.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aNegotiation in business. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aLabor History. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Negotiating.2bisacsh1 aBazerman, Max H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaumont, Phillip B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBendersky, Corinne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutcher-Gershenfeld, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Paul S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenhalgh, Leonard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeckscher, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffman, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Laurence C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Janice A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKochan, Thomas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKochan, Thomas A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLewicki, Roy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipsky, David B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipsky, David B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacduffie, John Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKersie, Robert B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMckersie, Robert B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreston, Lee E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRousseau, Denise M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc